issue.title: Review the text processing pipeline
issue.body:
## Context
Given the current pipeline: 
1. Casing normalization

Baseline: 
```python
def lowercase(text):
    return text.lower()
```

Modified:  N/A

2. Punctuation removal: 

Baseline: 
```python
def punctuation_removal(text):
    translator = str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)

    return text.translate(translator)
```

Modified:  N/A

3.  Tokenizer: 

Baseline: 
```python
def tokenize(text):
    return nltk.word_tokenize(text)
```

Modified:  N/A

4. Stopword removal: 

Baseline: 
```python
def remove_stopwords(tokens):
    stop_words = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')

    return [token for token in tokens if token not in stop_words]
```

Modified:  N/A

5. stemming

Baseline: 
```python
def stemming(tokens):
    stemmer = nltk.PorterStemmer()

    return [stemmer.stem(token) for token in tokens]
```

Modified:  N/A

## Some consideration
- Using better stemming strategy 
- Should we replace stemming by Lemmatization 
- Should we extract more features: words count, ratio of CAP (as a pam indicator), some meta data like has_url; has_phone,.. 
- Should we improve the tokenization


A/C: 
1. Check if there is anything we could improve.

For those requiring US-based hosting, [SonarQube Cloud US](https://sonarqube.us/) offers the perfect alternative. If you need data residency outside the US or within the EU, [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/) with this GitHub app is the ideal solution.

SonarQube Cloud integrates seamlessly into your GitHub workflow and provides clear guidance for resolving any code quality and security issues detected. The majority of popular languages can be analyzed automatically; no configuration is required!

With [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/github), you get:

-   Fast, precise static analysis and feedback on your code
    
-   Support for popular languages, frameworks, and IaC tools
    
-   Free analysis for open-source projects and private projects up to max 50k LoC
    
-   Automatic analysis of pull requests and branches with results reported inline
    
-   IDE Support with [SonarQube for IDE](https://www.sonarsource.com/products/sonarlint/) integration
    
-   Quality Gate (added as a GitHub check) acting at two different levels - first, preventing you from merging pull requests that contain issues - and later, helping you to release only clean, safe code
    
-   Sign up for SonarQube free tier and begin scanning your private and public repositories
    

A [GitHub Action](https://github.com/marketplace/actions/sonarcloud-scan) is available in the marketplace to make it easy for you (for projects where automatic analysis isn't available). SonarQube Cloud also integrates smoothly with Jenkins, CircleCI, TravisCI, CirrusCI, and many other tools.

A free tier is available that allows you to explore the benefits of SonarQube Cloud using your public and private repositories. We also provide a no-commitment, [14-day trial](https://www.sonarsource.com/products/sonarcloud/signup/) of SonarQube Cloud Team for unlimited team members, up to 1.9M LoC, AI CodeFix recommendations, and more. No need to speak with a sales rep or request a license key - get automatic code analysis results on your private projects in minutes! Want to see more examples of SonarCloud in action? You can [explore current Open Source projects in SonarCloud](https://sonarcloud.io/explore/projects?sort=-analysis_date) that are using the [Clean as You Code](https://www.sonarsource.com/solutions/our-unique-approach/) methodology.

issue.title: Qwen3 MoE Tool Usage Failures
issue.body: Seeing issues such as https://github.com/antinomyhq/forge/issues/1354 all related to tool use at this point (now that #261 is in). Qwen3 Coder should not be failing file operations all of the time trying to write code to actual files and i'm now seeing the same failure (agent/app believes it called a tool but gets unexpected results or none at all) modality from several distinct client types. They use a specialized tool template according to their docs - is something additional needed to leverage that?

comment.body:
> Prefill chunking definitely helps w/ OOMs on FP16 and tool use works across the board that way - this is test construction remedy on a websearch lib i'm toying with for `mistral.rs` use and rust-based agents/MCPs:
> 
> Looking at the code more carefully, I see the issue. The problem is that the mock server is expecting a JSON response but the test is trying to parse it as a SearXNGResponse struct, and there's likely a mismatch in the expected response structure or the way the mock is 
> set up. 
> 
> Looking at the error and the implementation, I need to check if the mock server is actually returning what the client expects. Let me first examine the full structure of the response and then fix the test properly.
> 
> Let me also look at the actual search method implementation to understand what's happening:
> ⏺ [09:39:11] Read src/lib.rs [Range 150-200]
> Let me look at the actual search method implementation to understand how it makes the request:
> ⏺ [09:39:34] Read src/lib.rs [Range 100-150]
> Now I need to see the complete search method implementation to understand how it makes the request:
> ⏺ [09:39:57] Read src/lib.rs [Range 180-220]
> Let me see the actual request part:
> ⏺ [09:40:36] Read src/lib.rs [Range 220-240]
> ⏺ [09:40:43] Read src/lib.rs [Range 240-280]
> ⏺ [09:40:51] Read src/lib.rs [Range 280-320]
> ⏺ [09:40:58] Read src/lib.rs [Range 1-40]
> we're no longer seeing the `<tool info>` stuff but actual execution of the tools available.
> 
> Requires a minimum of 4 32G GPUs so i can't quite check on the 2-way but it does indicate that we're getting corruption in the quantization process **or the fused moe mechanism itself.** I am able to reproduce this on a single GPU with `--m unsloth/DeepSeek-R1-0528-Qwen3-8B-GGUF --f DeepSeek-R1-0528-Qwen3-8B-Q4_K_M.gguf` which as i understand it uses the R1 fusedmoe implementation vs the qwen3 one and while its extremely fast, it _also_ fails to use tools correctly but doesn't produce the myriad textual artifacts we see with q3coder.
> 
> So far the symptoms i've seen are errant EOS tokens, substitution of `>` with `}`, and the hallucinatory repetition thing especially with large volumes of data. Wondering if a warning should be printed for users of quantized q3moe until this is addressed - too many horror stories of agents doing bad things to code and this model is extremely likely to be used in that way.

There are some reports that qwen3 coder may not work well with tool usage https://github.com/QwenLM/Qwen3-Coder/issues/499 

DeepSeek-R1-0528-Qwen3-8B: this model is not a MoE model, it is a LLaMa dense model.

issue.title: Refactor: Split large CLI command files into logical modules
issue.body:
## Summary

This PR refactors the large CLI command files into focused, maintainable modules. The refactoring improves code organization while maintaining 100% backward compatibility.

## Files Refactored

### 📧 **`email.rs`** (867 lines → 6 modules)
- **`analytics.rs`** - Email tracking and analytics functionality
- **`core.rs`** - Core email operations (send, setup)
- **`providers.rs`** - Provider operations (test, configure, switch)
- **`queue.rs`** - Queue operations (status, process, clear)
- **`templates.rs`** - Template management (list, validate, render)
- **`testing.rs`** - Testing/capture functionality (capture, list, show, clear, export)

### 🔄 **`queue.rs`** (795 lines → 3 modules)
- **`queue_work.rs`** - Work processing functionality for background job execution
- **`queue_status.rs`** - Status monitoring functionality for queue inspection
- **`queue_scheduler.rs`** - Scheduled commands and daemon functionality for cron-like jobs

### 🔐 **`auth.rs`** (761 lines → 3 modules)
- **`auth_setup.rs`** - Auth system setup and configuration
- **`auth_scaffold.rs`** - Scaffolding (user models, controllers, migrations)
- **`auth_generators.rs`** - Key generation functionality

### 🆕 **`new.rs`** (492 lines → 2 modules)
- **`new_app.rs`** - Main application creation functionality
- **`new_templates.rs`** - Template generation and file creation

### ⚙️ **`interactive_setup.rs`** (410 lines → 2 modules)
- **`interactive_wizard.rs`** - Interactive project setup wizard functionality
- **`interactive_config.rs`** - Configuration collection and generation

## Key Benefits

- ✅ **Improved maintainability**: Each module has a single, focused responsibility
- ✅ **Better code organization**: Related functionality is grouped together logically
- ✅ **Enhanced readability**: Smaller, more manageable files are easier to navigate
- ✅ **Zero breaking changes**: All existing functionality preserved with the same public API
- ✅ **Consistent patterns**: Modular structure follows the same pattern across all commands
- ✅ **Future development**: New features can be added to the appropriate module

## Testing

All functionality has been thoroughly tested:

- ✅ **Build verification**: `cargo build` completes successfully with no errors
- ✅ **CLI functionality**: All commands work exactly as before
- ✅ **Help system**: All help commands display correctly
- ✅ **Module integration**: Proper re-export structure maintains original public interface

### Command Testing Results
```bash
$ elifrs --help        # ✅ Main help works
$ elifrs email --help  # ✅ Email commands work  
$ elifrs queue --help  # ✅ Queue commands work
$ elifrs auth --help   # ✅ Auth commands work
```

## Technical Details

### Module Structure
Each refactored command follows this pattern:
```
crates/cli/src/commands/[command]/
├── mod.rs              # Module declarations and re-exports
├── [command]_[area].rs # Focused functionality modules
└── [command]_[area].rs # Additional modules as needed
```

### Backward Compatibility
- All original imports continue to work without modification
- External code using these modules requires no changes
- All CLI commands maintain their exact same behavior and help text

## Code Quality

- **Focused modules**: Each module has a clear, single responsibility
- **Clean separation**: Related functionality is properly grouped
- **Consistent imports**: All dependencies correctly maintained across modules
- **Documentation**: Each module includes appropriate documentation
- **Error handling**: All original error handling logic preserved
